## Part II: Architectural Feasibility

### What You're Actually Building (Core Components)

Based on your previous design decisions and this methodology:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[User Input<br/>Natural Language] --> B[LLM<br/>Fact Extractor]
    B --> C[Belief Store<br/>Bipartite Inference Graph]
    C --> D[Contradiction<br/>Detector]
    D --> E{Conflict?}
    E -->|Yes| F[Revision Engine<br/>Dirty Propagation]
    E -->|No| G[Insert Belief]
    F --> C
    G --> C
    C --> H[Query Handler]
    H --> I[Prompt Constructor]
    I --> J[LLM<br/>Reasoner]
    J --> K[Response + New Beliefs]
    K --> C
```

| Component | Complexity | Feasibility in 5 weeks |
|---|---|---|
| Belief Store (NetworkX bipartite graph) | Medium | ✅ Very doable — you've already designed the schema |
| Contradiction Detector (attribute clash lookup) | Low | ✅ Trivial — hash map check |
| Dirty Propagation (BFS on graph) | Low | ✅ Standard NetworkX traversal |
| Lazy Re-derivation on Query | Medium | ✅ Doable — most complex logic piece |
| LLM Fact Extraction (NL → structured triple) | Medium | ⚠️ Depends on prompt engineering quality |
| Prompt Constructor (belief injection) | Medium | ✅ Doable with your existing design |
| LLM Reasoning (derive conclusions) | Medium | ⚠️ Reliability depends on LLM choice |
| Evaluation harness (Belief-R style) | Medium | ✅ If scoped to a small test suite |
| Z3 integration | High | ❌ Cut this |
| ATMS / multiple worlds | High | ❌ Cut this |
| DiskCache + Pydantic enforcement | Low | ✅ Nice-to-have, add if time permits |
| POLARIS-style orchestration | Very High | ❌ Enterprise system, not a thesis deliverable |

### The LLM Reliability Problem

The methodology underestimates the single hardest engineering challenge: **LLM output parsing reliability.** When you ask an LLM to extract facts into `(subject, relation, object)` format, it will:

- Sometimes return valid triples
- Sometimes return free-text explanations instead
- Sometimes hallucinate relations that don't exist in your ontology
- Sometimes merge multiple facts into one triple incorrectly

This is where **Pydantic / instructor** actually matters — not as a "nice-to-have" but as a **critical reliability layer**. I'd prioritize this over Z3, ATMS, and most other fancy components.

```python
from pydantic import BaseModel
from typing import Literal

class BeliefUpdate(BaseModel):
    subject: str
    relation: str
    object: str | int | float | bool
    source: Literal["user_input", "llm_derivation", "system"]
    confidence: float = 1.0
```

Force the LLM to output this schema. If it fails validation, retry with the error message. This is your "defensive programming" — simple, battle-tested, and essential.

